from here. And they manufactured and fabricated 
the doors and then brought them up and installed

25:36.599 --> 25:42.747
them and so on. And these shelters were designed to 
withstand like a nuclear blast? Well, not a direct

25:49.863 --> 25:51.685
nuke. No, of course not. But they were principally 
designed against just a high explosion.

26:03.758 --> 26:12.548
When you start designing against nuclear, you're 
just making it too costly to protect one bird, one

26:03.758 --> 26:12.548
aircraft. These were above ground. Oh yeah, above 
ground. And armor plated doors.

26:24.519 --> 26:34.374
They, well, you just don't go through something of 
that magnitude without having different

26:24.519 --> 26:34.374
challenges. What else besides, did you finish 
those? Oh yeah, we finished them. So now we have

26:40.658 --> 26:43.383
these shelters at every air base? In Germany. Oh, 
in Germany? Yeah, not in England. Okay. Then we

26:48.591 --> 26:53.019
were bringing the F-111 in to England. And, of 
course, we had been working on that while I was over

26:53.740 --> 26:58.428
there in England. And, of course, it wasn't yet 
completed. That's the one place that we did have

27:03.196 --> 27:05.620
to... come up with new stories because what we had 
had in there before then was reconnaissance type

27:06.106 --> 27:16.861
aircraft, not bombers. So we had the new problems 
there. How did you resolve those? Well, just lots

27:24.032 --> 27:31.202
of meetings with British people and British 
agencies and so on. Were the British still

27:31.655 --> 27:36.163
sympathetic to having nuclear warheads? The 
government was. Of course, some of the people in

27:38.047 --> 27:39.930
the countryside. That's good old farmland that 
you're taking away from us. Let's see, the heart

27:47.124 --> 27:53.916
shelters,

28:10.467 --> 28:23.343
The chief staff of the Air Force in Washington, 
General Ryan,

28:10.467 --> 28:23.343
I had briefed General Ryan a number of times. In 
fact, I had briefed him on the F-111 move and so on.

28:26.927 --> 28:33.074
And General Ryan lives here in San Antonio now. But 
he issued a policy that said, I want all

28:40.353 --> 28:50.022
headquarters moved to an air base, an air force 
base. An air force base, by definition, means

28:50.402 --> 28:54.887
you've got a runway. I don't want anything, 
industrial complex or something like that, move

28:54.907 --> 29:00.692
everything. He said, I want my people to be able to 
smell jet fuel. How are you going to think? flying,

29:07.471 --> 29:17.582
unless you see flying, unless you hear flying, and 
that was

29:07.471 --> 29:17.582
it. When I got to Wiesbaden, Germany, General 
Holzapfel called me in. He says,

29:21.947 --> 29:28.914
General Ryan says we're going to move to Ramstein. 
I said, all right. I said, I'll get down there and

29:31.217 --> 29:34.861
check the facilities out and so on. He said, wait a 
minute, wait a minute. More than that, I said,

29:38.504 --> 29:40.406
what's that? And he says, normally a move like this 
would be planned and written by ops plans or a

29:40.687 --> 29:54.104
planning program, somebody like that. He said, 
they've been fiddling around with this thing for

29:54.124 --> 29:57.148
over a year. They're finding a thousand reasons 
why this headquarters can't be moved to Ramstein.

30:05.558 --> 30:07.060
Yes, I could hear it coming. He says, you will write 
the plan to move this headquarters to Ramstein.

30:14.410 --> 30:16.132
Well, that's not really an engineer's job. Our job 
is to support it, to determine what facilities are

30:16.333 --> 30:23.243
needed, crank it into the plan, and everything. He 
says, don't come back and tell me why we can't go.

30:26.027 --> 30:31.055
Come back to the plan that says how we will go. He 
says, now, I realize I realize you're just a

30:31.075 --> 30:35.882
colonel. You're going to knock heads with a 
two-star general over there, and you're going to

30:36.689 --> 30:41.514
knock heads with a one-star general over there. 
But you just stay with it. I will announce the

30:45.598 --> 30:54.948
assignment tomorrow morning at the staff 
meeting, and I'll expect your full cooperation.

30:54.968 --> 30:56.750
We wrote the plan. Headquarters is now in 
Ramstein. And it moved. Did you have problems with

31:02.455 --> 31:04.958
your one- and two-star generals? Not when he says 
they're writing a plan. It's not why we can't move.

31:11.158 --> 31:13.381
It's how we're going to move. That was it. But I 
didn't know that they'd been messing around with

31:15.024 --> 31:21.694
it for a year and a half. Sure, over in England, we 
keep hearing, hey, the headquarter's got to move

31:21.714 --> 31:25.179
the ramps. Never happened. Never happened. Sure 
enough, he never came up with a plan. He just come up

31:28.244 --> 31:29.746
with a plan. He just gave you the responsibility. 
Yeah, that was it. Of course I had to find me some

31:33.980 --> 31:41.271
people in my own staff that could work on such a 
plant because that's not our daily work. But we did

31:41.311 --> 31:49.905
it and he

31:41.311 --> 31:49.905
moved. We had a real good guy that wasn't there very 
long and that was Jay Robin. He was I guess I don't

32:02.684 --> 32:04.386
guess we even overlapped. He was in there, and 
somebody had taken his job by the time I got there.

32:08.850 --> 32:20.702
But I

32:08.850 --> 32:20.702
mentioned this at breakfast this morning to 
another retired Air Force general about your

32:08.850 --> 32:20.702
experience with Jay and spending two days with 
him. And he said, why didn't you tell him to spend 30

32:20.722 --> 32:24.326
years with him like we did? He used to be the 
inspector general. That's a hell of a time.

32:34.257 --> 32:57.025
Another interesting thing, following the war,

32:34.257 --> 32:57.025
they established an organization of civilians 
called

32:34.257 --> 32:57.025
the General Service Unit. And it was made up of 
Germans, Turks, Italians,

33:05.712 --> 33:15.587
few Spanish, and it had one Air Force officer

33:05.712 --> 33:15.587
as its advisor.

33:18.872 --> 33:33.795
The whole thing was set up on a military 
organization, but they were all civilians, and

33:18.872 --> 33:33.795
they were all from the different nationalities 
that were just wandering around Europe trying to

33:18.872 --> 33:33.795
find a place, abbreviated the GSU.

33:38.146 --> 33:47.940
That unit did various jobs of construction. Most 
of the design we did in our own staff, then gave them

33:47.960 --> 33:51.845
the job. Anywhere we told them to go. Put them on a 
job in Turkey, lay a pipeline across the river,

33:55.851 --> 34:02.901
something like that. And they did jobs that had to 
be done in a hurry, that we couldn't take the time to

34:07.340 --> 34:20.716
go out to bid for, or it may be a job just to keep them 
occupied in order to keep the unit in being. And it

34:20.736 --> 34:29.426
was located at one of the bases, and I had a captain 
that was, believe it or not, a captain, not very

34:20.736 --> 34:29.426
much, but he was part of it. Most of the captains we 
put there were sharp guys, and they were their

34:29.446 --> 34:34.512
advisors. And any time they have a problem with our 
staff back at the headquarters, we'll lose up to

34:35.470 --> 34:44.905
the captain to wade in and help get the problem 
solved. But we use that unit all over Europe and

34:44.925 --> 34:51.957
into Turkey.

34:55.963 --> 34:59.689
It wasn't a case of election when one of their 
People that might say it was an officer level

35:00.293 --> 35:07.583
either left or died or retired or something like 
that. And the captain would come back to the boss,

35:07.603 --> 35:15.975
whoever's sitting in my chair, and say, OK, now 
we've got to decide who we're going to promote up.

35:15.995 --> 35:21.422
And they were organized along the military line, 
even though they were civilians. They had their

35:21.442 --> 35:24.987
own camp, their own dining halls, everything. The 
Air Force now has a number of units that were copied

35:29.993 --> 35:46.409
from that organization, but they are military 
organizations.

35:46.429 --> 35:50.293
Why'd you only stay at this job for one year, 1970 
and 1971? When

35:51.154 --> 35:58.161
you are a Brigadier General, or any kind of gun in 
the airport. When the chief of staff tells you to go

36:03.553 --> 36:13.802
over there and do that job, you say, yes, sir, or 
else you say, here's my badge. The General

36:15.483 --> 36:23.470
Holzapfel left as commander of USAID, of Air Force 
Europe. And General Jones, who is now the chairman

36:24.591 --> 36:28.114
of the Joint Chief, commander of USAFD. And he had a 
protege by the name of Bob Thompson that had been

36:33.806 --> 36:54.127
his engineer when he was a SAC commander at the base 
over in Louisiana. And he wanted Thompson to be his

36:54.147 --> 36:58.472
engineer. And it was as simple as that. He just 
tells the person, tells the general assignment

37:01.662 --> 37:06.189
officer, I want Thompson to come in. Now it's up to 
the general assignment to start, OK, what happens

37:06.890 --> 37:10.375
now? So this, remember I used the name McGarvey, 
was the engineer in

37:10.636 --> 37:23.095
the air staff when we were building Tuiwa. He got 
promoted from colonel to general. OK, he's now

37:25.499 --> 37:27.362
sitting out it. Air Force Logistics Command at 
Wright-Patterson, and he's been out there for a

37:28.388 --> 37:35.999
number of years, and it's about time that he would 
have an overseas assignment. So they picked

37:36.019 --> 37:43.069
McGarvey up, sent him overseas, and okay, you go in 
and take McGarvey's place at Wright-Patterson.

37:43.089 --> 37:45.833
Did you get an opportunity to meet General Jones? 
General Jones? Oh, yeah. What was your

37:47.596 --> 37:50.220
impressions of him? Oh...

37:56.288 --> 37:56.809
I never...

37:59.675 --> 38:12.109
I never really tried to draw

37:59.675 --> 38:12.109
to develop an analysis and say, what kind of guy we 
got here.

38:13.511 --> 38:24.504
When I knew him, he was in a very, very difficult 
position to

38:13.511 --> 38:24.504
say, this is the real guy. Because he was sitting as 
General Holzapfel's deputy. wearing three

38:29.510 --> 38:36.638
stars, but he knew that he was going to be the 
commander in just one, two, or three months. And

38:37.559 --> 38:50.995
that's a real bad time because, man, you're trying 
already to get things straightened out, to run the

38:37.559 --> 38:50.995
way you want them, you're trying to get your staff, 
you know, like General Goddard and I were in there

38:52.730 --> 38:55.513
in his office. General Goddard, again, is out of 
Washington. He came over and paid a visit. Out of

39:00.379 --> 39:02.982
courtesy, he said, well, I better go see Joan. When 
we walked out, Joan says, hey, guy, Goddard. He

39:07.247 --> 39:13.474
says, get Bob Thompson over here to be Hub's 
deputy, because when Hub leaves, I want him to be my

39:07.247 --> 39:13.474
engineer. So two steps out in the hall, I turned to 
Goddard, and I said, where am I going? He said,

39:19.081 --> 39:22.585
that's the first I heard, that you're going. Four 
stars have got that much power. And they should

39:25.483 --> 39:28.508
have. How did that make you feel, though? I went to 
Texas A&M. I've been exposed to a lot of things. I

39:36.279 --> 39:41.186
just turned to the director of engineering and, 
well, it looks like I'm going. Where am I going?

39:44.430 --> 39:47.354
Because I knew I'd already been to the charm 
schools. They went here on that promotion list.

39:49.177 --> 39:51.340
Immediately, boy, they bring all the new 
Selectees in, and we go through what's called a

39:52.214 --> 39:57.320
charm school for a whole week in Washington. Tell 
me about that. Oh, yeah. We're lectured to. Is this

40:01.366 --> 40:02.707
in all services? No, this is Air Force. OK. But we 
are lectured to by the chief of staff of all of the

40:05.150 --> 40:12.019
services, the commandant of the Marines, the 
chief of staff of the Army. Westmoreland talked to

40:12.540 --> 40:13.921
us. He talked to us and used every bit of his time and 
left no time for questions. We knew what was

40:20.176 --> 40:21.298
happening. Hell, we were loaded for it. Ran out of 
time. But anyway, all of the chiefs talked to us,

40:25.606 --> 40:35.483
and then we get certain rules that are laid down to 
us, you know, verbally, and then we get certain

40:25.606 --> 40:35.483
advice. Well, what kind of things do they tell you 
for this week? All colonels designate generals.

40:41.133 --> 40:41.654
That's right. Okay, and what do they tell you? 
What's expected of you as a general officer is what

40:43.447 --> 40:47.292
I was addressing a while ago. Instead of, you're no 
longer a colonel, you're a general officer.

40:50.797 --> 40:54.162
You've got more eyes watching you now than ever 
have watched you before. What you do in the public

40:54.843 --> 41:00.350
will be known, if it's wrong tomorrow, all over the 
world. Well, you can say these things in a hurry,

41:00.811 --> 41:12.407
but they're told to you from time to time as you're 
there and they talk about public relations. What

41:12.843 --> 41:15.567
other topics besides public relations? Probably 
getting along with Congress and stuff like that.

41:18.992 --> 41:19.793
Oh, yeah. The director of legislative liaison 
comes in and says, now, I know that some of you have

41:19.813 --> 41:25.241
never been on the Hill. Some of you have probably 
had more time on the Hill than I have. And lay it out.

41:33.714 --> 41:41.365
Then you will have a protocol-type dinner or lunch 
in which OK, now, let's go through some protocol.

41:43.938 --> 41:52.508
And it's just a wrap-up of everything you ought to 
know before you get out there and stump your toes.

41:52.528 --> 41:53.509
Sure. And then, of course, there's always the guy 
that's one of the top generals that has got a pretty

41:53.529 --> 42:07.705
good story about the, OK, now I'm going to give you 
some rules that you won't find anywhere.

42:07.725 --> 42:11.689
Don't let the bastards wear you down.

42:12.192 --> 42:16.157
Don't get between the dog and the lamppost.

42:16.958 --> 42:18.459
Explain what he's talking about. Damn easy now 
that you're a general to get caught between these.

42:26.288 --> 42:27.350
Just don't get in there. Watch.

42:33.517 --> 42:35.359
It's an interesting theory.

42:37.962 --> 42:39.904
But anyway, we stepped out of the into the hall and I 
turned to this Goddard and I said, where am I going?

42:43.914 --> 42:46.317
He said, I don't know, but you're going. I said, 
well, as soon as you got an idea, let me know. Well,

42:51.022 --> 42:52.504
it's about to be a good one. It'll be one of the major 
commands. OK. So off to log command at Wright Pack.

43:00.894 --> 43:04.778
And of course, the minute I get to log command, This 
four-star General Merrill that I had dealt with up

43:05.534 --> 43:12.321
in Hartford, Connecticut on the museum, he's 
still the commander. So I know the man. I don't have

43:14.242 --> 43:20.268
to go into a new man and say, hey, if you haven't 
heard of me, I've heard of you. It's just, hey,

43:20.308 --> 43:24.192
welcome aboard. There's your desk. Go. So you were 
the Logistics Command, 1971 to 72.

43:34.964 --> 43:38.429
The museum's already built up there. What other 
things are you working on? Okay. The logistics

43:41.533 --> 43:53.448
command, just briefly, in the Air Force, is 
responsible for all the supply and the

43:41.533 --> 43:53.448
refurbishment and modification of all the 
aircraft. And it has four huge depots. One at

43:58.175 --> 44:04.583
McClellan in California, one at Ogden, Utah, One 
at Oklahoma City, one here at San Antonio, one at

44:05.963 --> 44:13.432
Warner Robins. And any one of those five plants' 
facility is valued more than any one of the other

44:13.452 --> 44:28.269
installations in the airport, even more than the 
SAC places. Why? Because of their shops, their

44:29.050 --> 44:35.498
sizes of their warehouses, the automation. I'm 
not talking about the aircraft, I'm talking about

44:36.035 --> 44:41.221
the physical land. On top of that we've got our log 
command has four or five other smaller places that

44:42.603 --> 44:50.752
deal strictly in patrol with them or something 
like that. But these places are absolutely huge.

44:56.338 --> 45:00.523
All of them have the runways that are equal to the 
SAC bases because Here at Kelly, the C-5 comes in

45:00.908 --> 45:04.894
and the B-52s come in. They work on the B-52s here at 
Kelly in San Antonio. And each of the aircraft

45:09.200 --> 45:15.590
systems are assigned to one of these depots. They 
don't work on the F-111 at all. Five of them. They

45:18.233 --> 45:20.677
only work on the F-111 at one place. They only work 
on the C-5 here at Kelly. And so on. So this is the...

45:26.085 --> 45:30.291
And we were going through... An update and 
modification of facilities is not something that

45:31.030 --> 45:41.851
I started, but this general ahead of me, McGarvey, 
had started it, and it was a lap over. I inherited it

45:41.971 --> 45:54.034
and kept going on the time phasing that had been 
established to program and go to the Air Force and

45:41.971 --> 45:54.034
get it into the program before the Congress. get 
the authorization and appropriations to upgrade

45:54.824 --> 45:59.670
some of our ancient facilities. Because all these 
bases, if you knew them, are some of the oldest

45:59.690 --> 46:06.538
bases that are in the Air Force Headquarters. So 
you were making improvements? Well, what we call

46:07.920 --> 46:11.865
upgrades, yeah. That's a principle thing. Got 
there just in time for the opening of the Air Force

46:13.707 --> 46:17.852
Museum, by the way. Oh, great. Yeah. And the 
president was there to open it.

46:25.418 --> 46:44.045
And that was amazing because we had to establish a 
little cosmetic booth just inside the door so that

